on":"Which one of the following best describes the most commonly used class of puberty-suppressing medications?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gonadotropin-releasing hormone analogue","Gonadotropin-releasing hormone antagonist","Kisspeptin receptor antagonist","Kisspeptin analogue","Gonadotropin receptor antagonist"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most commonly used puberty-suppressing medications are \u003Cstrong\u003Egonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) analogues\u003C/strong\u003E. These medications initially stimulate GnRH receptors but with continuous exposure lead to receptor downregulation and suppression of gonadotropin release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are less suitable or not currently used for puberty suppression:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGnRH antagonists\u003C/strong\u003E directly block GnRH receptors but are not typically used for puberty suppression\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKisspeptin receptor antagonists\u003C/strong\u003E would theoretically suppress puberty but are not currently available for clinical use\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKisspeptin analogues\u003C/strong\u003E would stimulate rather than suppress puberty\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGonadotropin receptor antagonists\u003C/strong\u003E would act too far downstream in the pathway\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGnRH analogues are considered safe and effective, with effects that are reversible upon discontinuation of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) analogues suppress puberty by causing pituitary desensitisation and downregulation of GnRH receptors.","GnRH analogues are the standard medical treatment for delaying puberty in children with gender dysphoria or precocious puberty."],"references":["Kim EY. Long-term effects of gonadotropin-releasing hormone analogs in girls with central precocious puberty. Korean J Pediatr. 2015 Jan;58(1):1-7. doi: 10.3345/kjp.2015.58.1.1. Epub 2015 Jan 31. PMID: 25729392; PMCID: PMC4342775.","Guss C, Gordon CM. Pubertal Blockade and Subsequent Gender-Affirming Therapy. JAMA Netw Open. 2022 Nov 1;5(11):e2239763. doi: 10.1001/jamanetworkopen.2022.39763. PMID: 36318212; PMCID: PMC9793415.","Lissauer, T., \u0026 Carroll, W. (Eds.). (2021). Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book: Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60111"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16268"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60111"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T22:17:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T22:57:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8959"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74617"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attribut